  <name>2. Challenge</name>
  <summary>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" paraid="0" paraeid="{87ea9058-c7dd-4156-af5f-539d4c65b814}{103}" data-ccp-props="{&amp;quot;335551550&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335551620&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335559683&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559685&amp;quot;:10,&amp;quot;335559731&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559737&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562764&amp;quot;:2,&amp;quot;335562765&amp;quot;:1.14,&amp;quot;335562766&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562767&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562768&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562769&amp;quot;:6}"&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;Many educators find learning about systems challenging because they feel that so much of how the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;system works is out of their control. It might surprise you but students, volunteers, and even&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;administrators feel this way too. No matter what role they play, no one in the system has control&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;over everything. State mandates, politics, available funds,&amp;nbsp;professional development requirements,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;COVID regulations, and space constraints - can all create barriers to learning that are hard if not&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US"&gt;impossible to modify.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" paraid="0" paraeid="{87ea9058-c7dd-4156-af5f-539d4c65b814}{103}" data-ccp-props="{&amp;quot;335551550&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335551620&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335559683&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559685&amp;quot;:10,&amp;quot;335559731&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559737&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562764&amp;quot;:2,&amp;quot;335562765&amp;quot;:1.14,&amp;quot;335562766&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562767&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562768&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562769&amp;quot;:6}"&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;The good news from educational and neuroscience research is that while we cannot change the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;entire system, we can identify and reduce the barriers that impact participants’ ability to learn. We&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;can make things better! For example, administrators can provide flexible professional development&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;opportunities for educators that respond to what educators want to learn. Educators can design&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;learning environments that account for the ways adults learn and use these theories to help learners&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;build self-efficacy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" paraid="0" paraeid="{87ea9058-c7dd-4156-af5f-539d4c65b814}{103}" data-ccp-props="{&amp;quot;335551550&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335551620&amp;quot;:1,&amp;quot;335559683&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559685&amp;quot;:10,&amp;quot;335559731&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335559737&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562764&amp;quot;:2,&amp;quot;335562765&amp;quot;:1.14,&amp;quot;335562766&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562767&amp;quot;:0,&amp;quot;335562768&amp;quot;:4,&amp;quot;335562769&amp;quot;:6}"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;The first step is to identify the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;barriers in the system that we have control over&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;. In this section of&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;the module, we will hear from an administrator who works in adult basic&amp;nbsp;education&amp;nbsp;and we will&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span data-usefontface="false" data-contrast="none" xml:lang="EN-US" lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 1.7rem;"&gt;reflect on the strategies she uses to remove barriers and support all participants.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/divider-wave-1.png" alt="" width="1920" height="195" role="presentation" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
